<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-148-248 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 798 284</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  May 27 1991 v8 n21 p23(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Easing resale bans may alter int'l nets; legalization ofinternational resale may encourage carriers to expand services andslash prices.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Crockett, Barton.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Regulators and industry analysts believe that the internationaltrend towards deregulating simple resale of basic network serviceswill reduce international calling rates.andP;  Several countriesincluding Sweden, Canada, the US and Great Britain plan toderegulate or legalize simple resale practices.andP;  Simple resaleinvolves reselling both switched and dedicated network servicesover international private lines.andP;  Deregulation would result inlower international service prices because it would allow smallercompanies to compete with larger, established carriers.andO;Deregulation also would enable companies to offer services in morecountries than they are allowed to do so under present regulation.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     International TradeRegulationNetworksDeregulationInternational CommunicationsCompetitionCost Reduction.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   International simple resale at a glance. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>